ccessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDance is more than an aesthetic of life – dance embodies life. This is evident from the social history of jive, the marketing of trans-national ballet, ritual healing dances in Italy or folk dances performed for tourists in Mexico, Panama and Canada. Dance often captures those essential dimensions of social life that cannot be easily put into words. What are the flows and movements of dance carried by migrants and tourists? How is dance used to shape nationalist ideology? What are the connections between dance and ethnicity, gender, health, globalization and nationalism, capitalism and post-colonialism? Through innovative and wide-ranging case studies, the contributors explore the central role dance plays in culture as leisure commodity, cultural heritage, cultural aesthetic or cathartic social movement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aDancexAnthropological aspects. 0aDancexSocial aspects. 0aTourismxAnthropological aspects. 0aTourismxSocial aspects. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh1 aCarrausse, Séverine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes-Freeland, Felicia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKringelbach, Hélène Neveu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKringelbach , Hélène Neveu, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLüdtke, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcIntosh, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNájera-Ramírez, Olga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPotter, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScarangella-McNenly, Linda